      "content": "Originalism is a legitimate approach, but it's often used as a shield to prevent judges from considering the nuances of the text and the values of the time in which it was written. The idea that judges should only consider the original meaning of the text, without regard for contemporary values or societal context, is a form of judicial restraint that can lead to outdated and inflexible interpretations. In contrast, living constitutionalism allows judges to engage with the complexities of the text and the world in which it operates, making it a more responsive and adaptable approach to constitutional interpretation.",
